text: Been coming back to this Geoffrey Verity Schofield video whenever I'm thinking of tinkering with my back workouts, really great tidbits

Even though the USA didn't actually have an Air Force during WW2 they still talked about making an annual "Air Force Day" a national holiday after establishing it. In France I talked about Galkovsky's article on how Saint-Exupery's flights were preparation for a political career.

There's an entire semi-forgotten cult of pilots in the 20th century (that started with Lindbergh?) that no one talks about. In the USSR Valery Chkalov, a test pilot, was appointed as Stalin's best friend and they offered him to become head of the NKVD.

H. G. Wells was obsessed with the idea of all national states collapsing due to war and famine and an international organization of pilots operating out of Iraq restoring order using aerial bombardment and eventually establishing "pneumodespotism" aerial dictatorship world order.

I seriously hope they didn't actually deploy a pregnant woman in Ukraine for anything more than a photo op, but it still speaks volumes for the sick psychology of the people in charge of those propaganda efforts and the way they think that they assumed it could be a good idea.

It's like that humorous chapter from Svejk about going to volunteer for the front in a wheelchair, but not a joke. They see people as individual units without personality and "sacrifice" and "heroism" is an abstract value existing outside of real life context or logical reason.

You can be sure that the people who come up with stuff like "pregnant female soldiers on the frontlines" are the same people who came up with the stories of female snipers with 300 confirmed kills 80 years ago, you can understand their entire worldview from this idea's appeal.

A fried posted about how Pakistan's Air Force draws pilots from aristocratic Persian warrior lineages going back to the Mughal Empire. I've read Israel's military pilots are also a closed elite caste. In the USA even top political figures apparently don't know the Area 51 lore.
Test pilots are their own society

The King of Westphalia, Jerome Bonaparte, brother of Napoleon, presented with the head of Ferdinand von Schill, Prussian officer who revolted against him and was killed by a Danish hussar. Bonaparte gave the head to some Dutch surgeon who "collected oddities".
Von Schill's head "remained at the University of Leiden until 1837, when German patriots obtained it for the dedication of a Schill monument in Brunswick."
